      {
        "id": 2959341,
        "name": "Rich Brown",
        "username": "Rich_Brown",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/rich_brown/{size}/2408_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-08-18T04:37:49.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group quote-modified\" data-post=\"7\" data-topic=\"163331\">\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group quote-modified\" data-post=\"6\" data-topic=\"163331\">\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"163331\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>1962 is the best Coutet I ever had. In that year, it can play with Climens and even nip the heels of Yquem. If you ever see it, don\u2019t hesitate.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Thank you William, I will certainly keep my eyes open. Given that age, what would the color spectrum be on that? I\u2019ve seen some bottles of Sauternes in that age-range pretty dark, and others are still a deep golden color.</p>\n<p>Want to make sure I don\u2019t end up buying a bad/oxidized bottle.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>The 1962 isn\u2019t especially dark / saturated!</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I was able to find a 62 Yquem locally that was purchased on release so I snagged it because of your killer CT note William.  I (sadly) do not have a ton of reference points when it comes tp Yquem\u2026but I\u2019m really looking forward to this one  <img src=\"/uploads/db3686/original/2X/0/0ff9bfcdb0964982cd3240b6159868fbdf215b1a.gif\" width=\"24\" height=\"18\" alt=\"[cheers.gif]\" title=\"cheers\" class=\"animated\"></p>",
